<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>help someone to something • help someone with something</xh5><p> <i>help someone to something—</i>serve a person with food, drink, etc.: “Shall I give you some strawberries, Mr. Hervey,” said Lady Anne, “or will you let Helena <u>help you to</u> some cherries?”</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not fully correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>help oneself to something</b>—1. <i>give oneself smth. such as food (without permission):</i> The aroma was irresistible and I quickly <u>helped myself to</u> some crab meat on the table. 2. <i>steal smth.: </i>The robbers <u>helped themselves to</u> an undisclosed amount of cash, believed to be several thousand dollars, before fleeing the area.</p><p><i>help someone with something—</i>1. make it easier for a person to do smth. by providing assistance: Butch sent Willie some books to <u>help him with</u> grammar. 2. help a person to put on or take off clothing: Someone <u>helped Janson with</u> his coat, and he left the hall.</p> </entry>
